<DESCRIPT>  COLLEGE; FOOTBALL; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  One day after quarterbacking Colorado to an Orange Bowl victory and its first
national championship, Charles S. Johnson said he won't play football next
season as a fifth-year senior.;    Johnson, a 5-foot-11, 165-pounder who was
voted the Orange Bowl's most valuable player, said he plans to interview with
a soft-drink company for an internship and plans to take a June entrance
examination for law school.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COLORADO'S MVP HANGS UP CLEATS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  College Football
Notebook  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  MIAMI CONTRITE: Citing Miami's behavior in the Cotton Bowl, university
President Edward T. Foote II said he would meet soon with Coach Dennis
Erickson and would conduct his search for a new athletic director with the
Hurricanes' 202 yards in penalties fresh on his mind.;    By halftime of their
46-3 rout of Texas, the Hurricanes had set a Cotton Bowl record for yards
penalized, with 132. Athletic Director Sam Jankovich, who is leaving to join
the New England Patriots, sent a message to Erickson in the locker room: The
antics had to stop. Miami was penalized 70 more yards in the second half.;
ETC.: Notre Dame flanker-kick returner Raghib Ismail is talking of turning
professional instead of returning for a senior season. . . . Zora Zorich, 59,
mother of Notre Dame All-America nose tackle Chris Zorich, died of natural
causes in Chicago. . . . Colorado quarterback Darian Hagan underwent surgery
Wednesday on his left knee, injured in the Buffaloes' 10-9 Orange Bowl victory
over Notre Dame. . . . Les Steckel, a former Minnesota Vikings head coach, is
expected to join the Colorado staff as a replacement for receivers coach Don
Frease, the Boulder (Colo.) Camera reported today. Frease, a former San Jose
State assistant, has accepted a position with Vanderbilt, Colorado Coach Bill
McCartney said.  </TEXT>
